SIMPLE: spoil
RECORDS: 3

==== ENTRY 1 ====
HEADWORD: Spoil
<hw>Spoil</hw> <pr>(spoil)</pr>, <pos>v. t.</pos> <vmorph>[<pos>imp. &
p. p.</pos> <conjf>Spoiled</conjf> <pr>(spoild)</pr> or
<conjf>Spoilt</conjf> <pr>(spoilt)</pr>; <pos>p. pr. & vb. n.</pos>
<conjf>Spoiling</conjf>.]</vmorph> <ety>[F. <ets>spolier</ets>, OF.
<ets>espoillier</ets>, fr. L. <ets>spoliare</ets>, fr.
<ets>spolium</ets> spoil. Cf. <er>Despoil</er>,
<er>Spoliation</er>.]</ety> <sn>1.</sn> <def>To plunder; to strip by
violence; to pillage; to rob; -- with <xex>of</xex> before the name of
the thing taken; <as>as, to <ex>spoil</ex> one of his goods or
possessions</as>.</def> ⟦ldquo⟧Ye shall <xex>spoil</xex> the
Egyptians.⟦rdquo⟧ <rj><au>Ex. iii. 22.</au></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>My sons their old, unhappy sire despise,⟦br⟧
<qex>Spoiled</qex> of his kingdom, and deprived of eyes.</q>
<rj><qau>Pope.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>2.</sn> <def>To seize by violence; to take by force; to
plunder.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>No man can enter into a strong man's house, and <qex>spoil</qex>
his goods, except he will first bind the strong man.</q> <rj><qau>Mark
iii. 27.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>3.</sn> <def>To cause to decay and perish; to corrupt; to
vitiate; to mar.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>Spiritual pride <qex>spoils</qex> many graces.</q> <rj><qau>Jer.
Taylor.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>4.</sn> <def>To render useless by injury; to injure fatally; to
ruin; to destroy; <as>as, to <ex>spoil</ex> paper; to have the crops
<ex>spoiled</ex> by insects; to <ex>spoil</ex> the eyes by
reading.</as></def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Spoil</ent>⟦br⟧

==== ENTRY 2 ====
HEADWORD: Spoil
<hw>Spoil</hw> <pr>(spoil)</pr>, <pos>v. i.</pos> <sn>1.</sn> <def>To
practice plunder or robbery.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>Outlaws, which, lurking in woods, used to break forth to rob and
<qex>spoil</qex>.</q> <rj><qau>Spenser.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>2.</sn> <def>To lose the valuable qualities; to be corrupted; to
decay; <as>as, fruit will soon <ex>spoil</ex> in warm
weather</as>.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Spoil</ent>⟦br⟧

==== ENTRY 3 ====
HEADWORD: Spoil
<hw>Spoil</hw>, <pos>n.</pos> <ety>[Cf. OF. <ets>espoille</ets>, L.
<ets>spolium</ets>.]</ety> <sn>1.</sn> <def>That which is taken from
another by violence; especially, the plunder taken from an enemy;
pillage; booty.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>Gentle gales,⟦br⟧
Fanning their odoriferous wings, dispense⟦br⟧
Native perfumes, and whisper whence they stole⟦br⟧
Those balmy <qex>spoils</qex>.</q> <rj><qau>Milton.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>2.</sn> <def>Public offices and their emoluments regarded as the
peculiar property of a successful party or faction, to be bestowed for
its own advantage; -- commonly in the plural; <as>as, to the victor
belong the <ex>spoils</ex></as>.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>From a principle of gratitude I adhered to the coalition; my vote
was counted in the day of battle, but I was overlooked in the division
of the <qex>spoil</qex>.</q> <rj><qau>Gibbon.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>3.</sn> <def>That which is gained by strength or
effort.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>Each science and each art his <qex>spoil</qex>.</q>
<rj><qau>Bentley.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>4.</sn> <def>The act or practice of plundering; robbery;
waste.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>The man that hath no music in himself,⟦br⟧
Nor is not moved with concord of sweet sounds,⟦br⟧
Is fit for treason, stratagems, and <qex>spoils</qex>.</q>
<rj><qau>Shak.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>5.</sn> <def>Corruption; cause of corruption.</def>
<mark>[Archaic]</mark>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>Villainous company hath been the <qex>spoil</qex> of me.</q>
<rj><qau>Shak.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>6.</sn> <def>The slough, or cast skin, of a serpent or other
animal.</def> <mark>[Obs.]</mark> <rj><au>Bacon.</au></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><cs><col><b>Spoil bank</b></col>, <cd>a bank formed by the earth
taken from an excavation, as of a canal.</cd> -- <col><b>The spoils
system</b></col>, <cd>the theory or practice of regarding public offices
and their emoluments as so much plunder to be distributed among their
active partisans by those who are chosen to responsible offices of
administration.</cd></cs>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Spoilable</ent>⟦br⟧
